16 WHEREAS, in 2002, she assumed the pen name Mary Kay Andrews with the publication
17 of Savannah Blues, and in 2006, her novel Hissy Fit became her first New York Times
18 bestseller, followed by 15 more New York Times, USA Today, and Publisher's Weekly
19 bestsellers; and
20 WHEREAS, her Georgia-based novels have promoted the state and Southern culture to the
21 world, having been published in German, Italian, Polish, Slovenian, Hungarian, Dutch,
22 Czech, and Japanese; and
23 WHEREAS, she and her family divide their time between Atlanta and Tybee Island, Georgia,
24 where they enjoy cooking up new recipes in three restored beach homes—The Breeze Inn,
25 Ebbtide, and Coquina Cottage—all named after fictional places in Mary Kay Andrews'
26 novels and available for rent through Tybee Vacation Rentals; and
27 WHEREAS, in between cooking, spoiling her grandchildren, and plotting her next novel,
28 Mary Kay Andrews is an intrepid treasure hunter who enjoys junking and fixing up old
29 houses; and
30 WHEREAS, she brings joy and happiness to her family, her many friends and neighbors who
31 have the pleasure of knowing her, and millions of readers across the world who are
32 transported by her novels to welcoming beaches, charming Southern towns, and large
33 personalities who can really those who throw humdinger hissy fits; and
34 WHEREAS, it is abundantly fitting and proper that the outstanding accomplishments of this
35 remarkable and distinguished Georgian be appropriately recognized.
